  <!-- =============================== -->
  <!-- Lessons three-up -->
  <!-- =============================== -->
  <section class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-24 md:py-32">
    <p class="eyebrow mb-3">What I learned</p>
    <h2 class="font-display text-display-md text-ink leading-tight max-w-[28ch] mb-16">
      Three lessons for anyone building a customer signal system.
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 md:gap-8">
      <div class="lesson-card">
        <div class="linocut-icon">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 80 80" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
            <rect x="14" y="14" width="52" height="52" fill="#E13D0F" stroke="#02101D" stroke-width="3"/>
            <line x1="22" y1="26" x2="58" y2="26" stroke="#F4EFE5" stroke-width="2"/>
            <line x1="22" y1="34" x2="58" y2="34" stroke="#F4EFE5" stroke-width="2"/>
            <line x1="22" y1="42" x2="50" y2="42" stroke="#F4EFE5" stroke-width="2"/>
            <line x1="22" y1="50" x2="58" y2="50" stroke="#F4EFE5" stroke-width="2"/>
            <line x1="22" y1="58" x2="44" y2="58" stroke="#F4EFE5" stroke-width="2"/>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <h3 class="font-display text-xl text-ink mb-4 leading-tight">Roadmap visibility beat feature voting.</h3>
        <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">
          Customers wanted to see where the product was going more than they
          wanted to vote on individual features. The format that scaled trust
          was transparency about direction, not democracy about details.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-card">
        <div class="linocut-icon">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 80 80" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
            <circle cx="26" cy="40" r="14" fill="#E13D0F" stroke="#02101D" stroke-width="2.5"/>
            <circle cx="54" cy="40" r="14" fill="#E13D0F" stroke="#02101D" stroke-width="2.5"/>
            <line x1="34" y1="40" x2="46" y2="40" stroke="#02101D" stroke-width="2.5"/>
            <circle cx="26" cy="40" r="4" fill="#F4EFE5"/>
            <circle cx="54" cy="40" r="4" fill="#F4EFE5"/>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <h3 class="font-display text-xl text-ink mb-4 leading-tight">Cross-functional ownership is the multiplier.</h3>
        <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">
          A program owned only by PX is a PX program. A program co-owned with
          CX, supported by Product, and connected to GTM becomes company
          infrastructure. The advocacy from the VP of CX was a turning point.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-card">
        <div class="linocut-icon">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 80 80" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
            <path d="M40 14 a26 26 0 1 1 -26 26" fill="none" stroke="#E13D0F" stroke-width="6" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            <path d="M40 14 L 30 8 L 30 20 Z" fill="#E13D0F"/>
            <circle cx="40" cy="40" r="6" fill="#02101D"/>
            <line x1="40" y1="22" x2="40" y2="34" stroke="#02101D" stroke-width="2"/>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <h3 class="font-display text-xl text-ink mb-4 leading-tight">The loop has to actually close.</h3>
        <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">
          Customers can tell when programs are extractive. The single biggest
          determinant of program credibility is whether customers see something
          come back. Without the return step, trust erodes faster than it built.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- =============================== -->
  <!-- Meta-point -->
  <!-- =============================== -->
  <section class="grid-backdrop overflow-hidden border-b border-ink/10">
    <div class="grid-backdrop-band-top"></div>
    <div class="grid-backdrop-band-bottom"></div>
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-28 md:py-36 relative z-10">
      <p class="eyebrow-voice mb-8">The meta-point</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-ink leading-[0.95] tracking-tight mb-12" style="font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 5.5rem);">
        Customer experience isn't just what happens inside the product.<br/>
        <span class="text-orange">It's how customers are brought into the evolution of the product.</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <p class="text-xl text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">
          During major transformation, trust is built through visibility,
          listening, education, and follow-through. The program design isn't a
          calendar of events. It's an operating contract between the company
          and its customers about how change happens. That's what makes it a
          system instead of an initiative.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

